The learning outcomes of private schools in Scotland have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good test results. Success has been reinforced by individual and community success in sports, art, music and other community projects.
These over 30,000 pupil schools located across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Board of Private Schools SCIS, strive to provide high-quality service to their pupils and their parents.
Private schools strive to prepare their students for their chosen careers, graduate and higher education, as well as for world citizenship.
As a player in the education sector who can design and implement customized learning content, we have noticed the status of languages as a preferred and desired learning material in continuing education institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in their own language, the message goes to their heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language if we want to build relationships with people in other countries.
From this year’s most recent test results, we find that languages are at the top of the lists in terms of access percentage among private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest A rating.
Based on the data collected from 74 SCIS schools, 72% of the pupils who received the best grade A studied Mandarin Chinese, 72% studied German, 69% studied French and 63% studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are considered to be of the same value as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the curriculum of private schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Employment Agency in 2014, 17% of situations where an employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by a lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary for the promotion of future career development for young people.
The more possible jobs require language skills, the more essential these skills will be in the global world.
If a person has studied another language, he or she will have an advantage in the future of this lifelong skill, regardless of which career he or she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner puts a language-savvy person automatically ahead of the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013, 75% of over 4,000 adults in the UK are unable to engage in conversation in a foreign language, and French was the only language with a double-digit figure of 15%.
For this reason, investing in language learning is now important for today’s children.
In particular, the ability to speak the languages of developing countries gives children a better opportunity to find a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some teach specifically languages that are supposed to be important to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Despite the interests of your child, there are always several language options in private schools taught by specialized teachers.
Private schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future brings.
It cannot be denied at this time that languages in the international business environment will continue to be very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Today’s languages should indeed be seen as ‘international communication skills’.
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, versatility and a high level of Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the SCIS Board of Scottish Private Schools
