WASHINGTON (Reuters) - North Korea's foreign minister told the U.N. on Saturday that continuing sanctions had only heightened confidence in the United States, and under these circumstances there is no possibility that North Korea would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho said at the UN General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant benevolent measures" over the past year, including stopping nuclear and missile tests, detonating the nuclear test site and promising that North Korea will not increase the number of nuclear weapons or technology.
"However, we have not seen a similar gesture from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we cannot be sure of maintaining national security, so under such circumstances, it is not possible to unilaterally disarm ourselves.”
While Mr Ri reiterated the fact that Washington does not accept a phased nuclear ceasefire, which would reward North Korea for every intermediate issue, his statement is nevertheless significant in the sense that unilateral disarmament has not been completely excluded, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement given by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first sitting US President-North Korean leader summit in Singapore on June 12, in a statement Kim assured "the Korean peninsula will be stripped of nuclear weapons" and Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought to formally end the 1950–1953 Korean War, but the United States has demanded that Pyongyang surrender its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed the easing of stringent international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The United States has called for ‘nuclear disarmament first,’ and has raised pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by means of violence – even opposing the ‘peace declaration’,” Ri said.
"The conviction that sanctions would get us on our knees is the wish of the indifferent.
But the problem is that continuing sanctions are only deepening our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans to host the next Kim-Trump summit, which Trump himself stressed to the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister underlined three meetings with South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea and not the United States were the party demanding disarmament, the situation would not have progressed to such an impasse."
Yet Rin’s tone of voice was significantly different from last year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that pointing missiles toward the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “bad President” Trump called Kim “suicidal” missiles.
Still last year, Trump threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea. However, this year, Trump praised Kim for his courage to approach a ceasefire, but still stressed that there is still much work to be done and sanctions must remain until North Korea gives up its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he has no time limit: “If it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia proposed that the UN Security Council should be rewarded for the progress made in Pyongyang.
