Harvard students complete a course that instructs them to a sufficient rest
All undergraduate students at Harvard University are taking part in this year’s course designed to increase student rest. The course is a countermeasure to the university’s thriving macho culture, where students weigh a long night with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite ignorant about basic issues related to their own well-being.
The course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of medicine at Harvard University, who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, believes the course will be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course by reading about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the lecture, I spoke to a young woman who said, ‘Why do I not hear about it until now, in my last year of college?’
“No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I found surprising,” he told the Telegraph.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how the right sleep habits support academic and athletic performance as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of medicine at Harvard University and vice president of health services at the University, said the university had completed a course after hearing students suffer from severe sleep deprivation during the week of study.
The one-hour course includes a set of interactive tasks.
In one section, students will be presented with a picture of the living room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, and thus get information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
The second section tells participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map, equipped with interactive icons, encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this does not have an immediate impact on student behavior.
However, we believe that they have the right to know about these things just as they have the right to know about the health effects caused by smoking,” Professor Czeisler adds.
All-night student marathons are still the subject of pride, according to Professor Czeisler, and current technology and the ever-increasing pressures of students have made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
“Getting enough and high-quality sleep should be a student’s ‘secret weapon’ against stress, fatigue and anxiety, and even weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state similar to starvation in the brain, which is why a person is constantly hungry,” the professor notes.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemistry and physical psychology in California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says that the course opened his eyes and gave the impetus to organise a course that encompasses all the students on the campus.
He hopes that all postgraduate students could complete a similar set of studies before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm clock to remind them of sleep time in addition to waking up in the morning, and encourages them to keep in mind the side effects of electronic displays and LED "blue light" on daily rhythms, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
